\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sa200\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32 Atari ST\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The Atari ST was a legendary 16bit computer of the Eighties.\par
Beside the price, its forces were a no-nonsense graphical operating system (the GEM, that also existed on the PC), a flicker-free high resolution monochrome display for professional use, and MIDI ports. Thanks to the latter, to usable hard drives and to tight timings provided by the hardware, the Atari ST was for a long while the computer of choice for musicians and studios, running the best MIDI software available at the time, such as Cubase and Notator. In this domain, the ST was number one. In fact it is still used in some studios.\par
Its native sound is produced by the modest YM2149 chip, which is not too good at sample playback but had some good tunes composed for it, and even a cool speech synthesiser that has been used in commercial records.\par
The ST struggles on scrolling action games because its chipset wasn't dedicated to that sort of childish programs, it was a serious computer in the beginning. The STE version is better in this respect, in other words, less serious.\par
The ST has a great collection of games nevertheless, including action games, including scrollers.\par
Unlikecomputers today, the ST featured two useful keys: Help and Undo (mapped to Page Up and Page Down in Steem!)\par
Downsides of the ST were that earlier models were sold with single-sided drives, the OS in ROM couldn't be easily fixed, memory wasn't easily expandable and viral piracy readily killed the platform, especially in the USA.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sa200\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32 Steem\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\expndtw15\fs28 Steem Engine, by Anthony & Russell Hayward\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22 Steem is a legendary Atari ST emulator for the PC, both accurate and easy to use thanks to its great user interface. Its development was stopped in 2004, at v3.2. The Steem authors probably got sick of all the lamers. In 2011 the Hayward bros released the source code for further development.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28 Steem SSE\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22 Steem SSE stands for \b\i ST\b0  \b E\b0 nhanced \b EM\b0 ulator \b S\b0 ensei \b S\b0 oftware \b E\b0 dition\i0 . It is an updated version of Steem. \lang6153 Some say an improvement, some say it's worse!\par
\lang2057 Features have been added and emulation has been refined. Steem SSE's goal is to keep the Atari ST alive in the hearts and minds of old and new generations. \par
