\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Reset\par
\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 A left click on the reset button emulates the reset button of the ST (warm reset).\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Notice that some demos were programmed to react on reset (hidden screen and such). \par
A right click emulates switching off, waiting as long as necessary for the RAM chips to clear (which could be minutes on a real ST), switching on again, except it's instant (don't think we'll get requests for precise delay).\par
Keyboard shortcuts may be assigned to warm or cold reset as well.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Play\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 You start/stop emulation by using the play button or the \b F12\b0  function key.\par
\par
If you right click on \i Play\i0 , you advance in slow motion. The speed can be set in Options/General. For technical reasons, sound still plays if option \i Emulation thread\i0  is active.\par
\par
When emulation starts, the mouse cursor may be grabbed by Steem. You may change this (tricky) behaviour in the options. In that case, the mouse still controls Windows, and you can stop emulation by clicking on \i Play\i0  again. If you click in the window, the mouse will be grabbed in \i auto\i0  mode. Once it is grabbed, you may wonder how to free it? \b F11\b0  toggles mouse capture.\par
So \b F11\b0  and \b F12\b0  are the main Steem SSE control keys. They were chosen because the ST had function keys F1 to F10. Yet you may change this in the options, it is possible to use \b pause\b0  and \b shift pause\b0  instead.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Fast forward\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Use this to skip boring intros. You may still expect accurate emulation. Steem uses more CPU power.\par
Right clicking on this also activates the \i lightsearch\i0  (check if there is some picture hidden by colour definitions).\par
If you double click on this button (with the left or right button) it will stick down, so you don't have to hold down the button for particularly long waits.\par
For technical reasons, sound still plays if the \i Emulation thread\i0  option is active.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Memory snapshot\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 The camera and chip button on the Steem toolbar brings up a menu from which you can load and save memory snapshots. Save snapshot will save out the current state of the ST (not just RAM) to a file. \par
This can be useful for games without save facilities.\par
When you load a snapshot it will change your TOS version, monitor type, memory size and the current disks in the drives. The last ten snapshots that have been used appear also on this menu so you can quickly reload them. \par
There is also an option to undo the last snapshot load or reset in case you did it by mistake or it failed. \par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  Memory snapshots of 32bit and 64bit builds are not mutually compatible\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Screenshot\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Use the right mouse button to choose your options and the left one to record a screenshot.\par
The D3D builds of Steem SSE can natively save a screenshot as a BMP, JPG, PNG or NEO file.\par
The DD builds of Steem SSE can natively save in BMP or NEO format.\par
With the FreeImage.dll plugin, more formats and options are available (hint: use the last version).\par
PNG is the recommended format because it is both small and lossless. Notice that JPG is a lossy format, only appropriate for a very colourful screen.\par
NEO is the format used by Neochrome on the ST. It is only appropriate when there is no overscan and no palette trick.\par
It is also possible to save multiple screenshots in a row using a shortcut. \par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Note: Recording the video\tab\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Although you can assign a shortcut to internal ST video recording (DirectDraw builds only), this isn't recommended as it is far too slow. It is better to use a third-party tool or Windows 10's own recorder (Windows key + G), which efficiently produces MP4 files.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Paste\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 This button allows you to quickly and easily paste text from Windows into the ST. Just click on the button and Steem will type in the text at incredible speed. Some programs may struggle with the top speed, to slow it down right click on the button and choose a longer delay. \par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Disk manager\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 The icon toggle Steem's disk manager (see below).\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Joysticks\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 You can assign keys or real (PC, USB) joysticks to ST joystick ports 0 and 1 and to STE joysticks, and even to parallel port joysticks.\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 Most games use standard port 1 for one player game\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  If the standard port 0 is selected, the mouse is disabled, as on a real ST (had a lot of bug reports for that)\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  Key definitions for joysticks may interfere with keyboard emulation\par
Steem handles analogue as well as digital PC joysticks.\par
Six setups may be recorded. In each, joysticks may be always active, never active, or active or not according to the state of your PC keyboard Num Lock and Scroll Lock keys. If those keys are not on your keyboard, you may assign shortcuts (Toggle Joystick ... select) instead with the same effect. A shortcut can also select the setup.\par
For "up" you have 2 boxes, so you can map a joystick button for jump as in arcade games, in addition to the joystick movement. Unfortunately, ST joysticks only had one button. \par
F11 or Pause to remove a key selection.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Patches\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Patches (file extension STP) change the memory of the ST after a program has been loaded to change its behaviour.\par
This is useful to go around a bug or a protection, cheat in some game, etc.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  You may use the debugger to probe the ST program and create your own patches with a text editor\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Shortcuts\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 You can assign key combinations (up to 3 keys each) to either some Steem control (start/stop, fullscreen, etc.) or some Atari ST key.\par
Not only keys are taken as shortcuts but also mouse and joystick buttons.\par
You can load and save as many key sets as you wish and use several of them at the same time.\par
To avoid overwriting your changes, it's advised to name your own sets rather than edit the Default set.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  You can scroll the list using only the keyboard when the focus is on a Del button. F11 to remove a key selection.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Settings\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 The icon makes the extensive options dialog of Steem (see below) appear or disappear.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Debugger\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 This icon, an ST bomb, is only available in the Debug builds. It toggles the Debugger windows. For some information about the debugger, consult the Debugger release notes. It is not really covered by this manual. \par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Info\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 The blue 'i' icon opens an information box that can display this very manual and other useful documentation, and the \i TRACE.txt\i0  debug file if it exists. Pressing F1 when the emulator is stopped also opens that box. Esc closes the box.\par
\b Status\b0\par
A page in this window displays program statistics and the current state of chips (68000 etc.) \par
Most figures are reset at each run (from start to stop by using the icons or F12 or some shortcut), those that are not are displayed in deep blue.\par

\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa160\sl240\slmult1 The 4096 colour palette is an STE feature, but notice that a program written for the STF may accidentally use the extra STE bits, and the STE TOS itself uses that extended palette on boot. TOS also sets up default MicroWire settings, and it uses the video timer B on boot. So you need to be careful when interpreting statistics, that's why some are split between TOS and program use.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Computing statistics may take a while if the current frame contains many colours. For this reason, they are computed only when the \i Status\i0  info page is active (or when you open it). The colour count comprises OSD if present and maxes out at 4096.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}The reported CPU usage, in %, can be higher than in the task manager if your CPU is throttled.\par

\pard\sa160\sl240\slmult1\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32\lang1033 Status bar\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Steem SSE optionally features a status bar.\par
There are 4 parts. Each part can be toggled between two uses by a mouse click .\par

\pard 
{\pntext\f1 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf1\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li360\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Frequency/mouse coordinates\line If VSync is engaged, the first figure is for the ST, the second for the current PC screen.\line Mouse coordinates are displayed if the ST address where they are stored is made available to Steem SSE. There are two ways to do it: By specifying MouseAd in an ini file, or by using the \i emu detect\i0  capacity on ST address $ffc10a.\par
{\pntext\f1 2.\tab}Useful info/Configuration description\par
{\pntext\f1 3.\tab}Configuration info and icons/searchlight \line The searchlight is the same feature as when you right click on fast forward, but without fast forward.\par
{\pntext\f1 4.\tab}CAPS NUM SCRL state/disk info\line CAPS NUM SCRL info is handy if you don't have leds on your keyboard (remote keyboard, laptop...) \line Disk info is an alternative to the OSD option.\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf4 Tip\cf0  Multiple status bar refreshes due to drive operation can be a drag on the system\par
\par
Steem SSE may also use the status bar to communicate some funny issues such as...\par
 \fs24 HALT\fs22\par
In some conditions, the ST processor (MC68000) can \i halt\i0 , that is stop operating.\par
It generally means the program it was running crashed, and it's not possible to recover from this situation. This may be an emulation bug or, more likely, not (bad disk image, buggy ST program, etc.) The ST won't run again, it must be reset or rebooted.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  On real hardware, the rest of the system may sometimes still run somewhat, but this is not emulated in Steem SSE\par
\par
 \fs24 BLIT ERROR\fs22\par
Problem with video rendering. In some cases, Steem SSE can recover, in others you have to leave or even use the task manager to kill Steem SSE. Sorry.\par
It happens regularly when you stop emulation. In that case it isn't important (well, I should debug that!)\par
Also, if you see GDI on the status bar, it means DirectX stopped working and you'd better restart Steem SSE. Those issues mostly happen with fullscreen endeavours going wrong, or power management interfering. Or maybe the \i No DirectX\i0  startup option is checked.\par
\par
 \fs24 6301 CRASH\fs22\par
The keyboard controller (6301) emulation hanged.\par
\par
SYSTEM ERROR\par
Steem SSE caught a system exception. The most prudent approach is to leave, but in some cases, you can resume emulation. If you quit while this message is showing, Steem SSE won't attempt to save the configuration in \i steem.ini\i0  in order to avoid file corruption (you still should make regular backups).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sa200\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32\lang1033 Options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Steem is a very complete emulator and there are really many options, spread on several pages (or tabs). All are explained here, tab by tab.\par
Some options can be changed only when the \i Show all settings\i0  box has been checked on the \i Misc.\i0  page. They are marked with a star (*) in this manual.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  In Steem SSE you can change almost all options live, that is when the emulator is running. This is handy but not guaranteed to work all the time. After all, buffers are created, moved, deleted on the fly, and changing an option could alter a buffer while it is being used.\par
This is especially the case when the \i Emulation thread\i0  option is checked: you really have two threads running on the same data set, and there are only a few locks in Steem SSE. Freezes and crashes when changing display and sound are possible.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Startup\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 You need to quit and restart Steem for those options to have effect.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Only one Steem SSE\fs22\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1 If you want to start Steem SSE (v4.1+) again, directly or by launching an associated file, it will go to your current instance instead.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Big GUI\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This setting may help for high DPI screens. You can also choose the font size, though the GUI was designed with the defaults in mind.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  Since v4.1, Steem SSE disables Windows scaling by default. If you wish you can override this by changing the DPI properties (right click on the icon, properties, compatibility, high DPI settings, check \i High DPI scaling override\i0 , select \i Scaling performed by: System\i0 ). \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Restore Previous State\fs22\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1 You can choose to have Steem remember the state of the ST when it quits, so you can return to what you were doing next time you run it. Below the option is a box where you can type in the filename that will be used to save the state, this file will be saved in the directory Steem is in.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  Sometimes, the file gets corrupted and makes Steem SSE fail, possibly crash. The solution is to delete it (the file).\par
If this option isn't checked, Steem SSE will load and display the startup.jpg picture instead. It looks for one in your settings path then in the application directory.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Run on startup\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 I did it to compare CPU use of instances of Steem SSE starting at the same time, but it can be handy in other cases.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Start in Fullscreen Mode\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 If DirectX is enabled and working, then you can make Steem fill the whole screen when it first runs, to impress your friends.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Lock window size\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When it's checked you can't change the size of the window by dragging the borders so that you won't be able to sabotage Steem's nice display. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Never Use DirectDraw/Direct3D /DirectSound\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 If you have DirectX errors when you boot up, or DirectX doesn't work properly, then you can tell Steem to not use it. Sound doesn't work without DirectSound and drawing is slower without DirectDraw. If you are having problems, it is best to install the latest version of DirectX through Windows Update.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  Really it shouldn't happen, this option was more useful in the time of Windows 95 when Steem first was released. What could happen is that those options are checked by accident. People using Wine to run Steem (for example the debugger, that is Windows-only) may also prefer GDI rendering.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 TRACE.txt\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 If checked, Steem SSE will write some debugging info in that file in its running directory. It will also dump your options when you close it.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  This option doesn't exist in beta builds, a trace file is always produced.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 General\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\expndtw0\fs24\lang2057 Run speed (hack)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Sometimes you will find a game/program that isn't significantly affected by changing CPU speed, it is still too slow. In that case you can use this option to change the speed Steem runs and make sure a program speeds up (or even slows down if you want). The disadvantage is that sound doesn't work above 105% or below 80%.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Slow motion speed\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This option determines how fast Steem will run when you have slow motion turned on (right-click on the play button).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Maximum fast forward speed\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Using this option, you can limit Steem's speed, fastest isn't always best (you can find you have zipped through the bit you wanted to see).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Show pop-up hints\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This little option toggles those pop-up hints on and off; now you've read the manual you don't really need them.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Make Steem high priority\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When this option is ticked Steem will get first use of the CPU ahead of other applications. This means Steem will still run smoothly even if you start doing something in another window at the same time, but everything else will run slower.  It's at your discretion which processes are more vital on your computer. The spreadsheet or Steem?\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  This does make a difference for a stable frame rate when your computer gets busy (internet browser, disk activity...)\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Emulation thread\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This option could make Steem SSE more responsive. Steem gets a tad more system resources for its supplementary thread. When it's checked, you may change any other options you like live (emulation running), but there's no guarantee it will not crash!\par
Noticeably, with the apart thread, emulation isn't stopped when you move any Steem window and the sound doesn't loop. When the emulation thread crashes or stalls, you can kill it using F12 or the classic menu.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  The shortcut for double clicking in the ST requires this option\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  With the debugger, effects are unpredictable\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Pause emulation when inactive\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When this option is checked Steem will pause emulation when you switch to another program. Steem uses some PC CPU time when running which may slow other programs down, if you are switching between programs regularly you may want to use this option.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Disable system keys when running\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This option allows you to send certain key combinations that are used by Windows to the ST instead. When it is checked Alt+Tab, Ctrl+Esc and Ctrl+Alt+Delete will go to the ST instead of to the PC. Although Steem is very stable this option could cause a bit of a disaster if Steem stops responding for any reason, you won't be able to shut it down with Ctrl+Alt+Delete, so for safety reasons it is best only to use this option when you really need it. \par
Unfortunately, this option doesn't always work in fullscreen mode. Depending on your version of Windows, it may not be possible to capture certain key combinations - you can use shortcuts (see below) to trigger the keys you want from other keys. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Start emulation on mouse click\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When checked clicking on Steem's main window will start emulation.\par
\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Machine\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\expndtw0\fs24\lang2057 ST Model\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The STE was the better computer but most programs were coded with the older STF (and 520ST) in mind. \par
Notice that there was no model called Atari STF or Atari STE, they had a number like 520ST, 1040STFM, 520STE. There were also Mega models.\par
In Steem SSE, the Mega ST is like an STF with a blitter and a Ricoh real time clock. Its CPU clock is different (8010613Hz instead of 8021247Hz). You choose the memory. If you want to emulate the keyboard with Cherry black switches, you need to purchase a mechanical keyboard!\par
If you use a US TOS, the CPU clock will also be different on the STF (8010600Hz) and the STE (8053976Hz): those are the NTSC variants.\par
The Mega STE uses the same CPU clock as the STE, but it can programmatically switch to 16MHz too. It also has the Ricoh RTC. It can use 1.44MB disks. By convenience, other models can too (hack). The turbo button (hack) commands the Mega STE's CPU cache and speed.\par
The STFM (*) is almost like the STF, it just has some more bus errors on STE-only device addresses. Not all STF and STFM behaved that way, but some exemplars certainly did and we emulate those.\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Clock (hack)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 You can set the clock of both the CPU. It is a hack that can boost the speed of the emulated ST, to improve those painfully slow games that were released.  The ST's CPU ran at 8 megahertz but here you can whack it up to get things going faster. A couple of points: setting the CPU speed above 8MHz will cause the emulator to run \b slower\b0 , because it has more processing to do for each screen displayed. It will also cause many ST programs to crash/not work properly, because they rely on the processor running at the correct speed. If you want really high speed (512mhz and above), you may prefer the 64bit builds of Steem SSE because it has larger cycle counters that make it safer.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  You don't need to change the setting if you want to run the Mega STE at 16MHz as on real hardware. On real hardware, the CPU clock is internally commanded. There's no \i turbo\i0  switch on the original machine, not even a GEM option (design fault in my opinion).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 RAM Memory\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Here you can select how much memory will be available in the virtual ST. \par
The most compatible choice is generally 1MB, some apps need more, some apps crash with 4MB.\par
12MB (*) includes 8MB of ALT-RAM as on the MonSTer board. A driver and an appropriate TOS (e.g. 2.06) are necessary to use that RAM.\par
Please note that 14MB (*) wasn't supported on the ST range of computers without special hacks, so not everything will work either with that option selected. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Cartridge (optional)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Steem can emulate ROM cartridges using cartridge images, here you can choose to insert one. For details how to make a cartridge image see the \i cart image howto\i0  file that comes with Steem.\par
\cf4 tip\cf0  Few cartridges were actually available. Generally the ST operated without a cartridge.\par
\i Switch off\i0  makes the cartridge transparent (or crashes Steem SSE if I forgot a bug). It's the same as if you removed the cartridge.\par
\i Freeze\i0  emulates the freeze button of the \i Multiface\i0  and \i Ultimate Ripper\i0  cartridges. For the latter, you need to select the appropriate Port connexion.\par
If you insert the (fake) MV16 cartridge image, Steem SSE will play the samples in the original B.A.T game. \par
Steem SSE also emulates playback of the Replay 16 cartridge (not recording).\par
\par
\cf1\b Active cartridges\cf6\b0\par
\cf0 Steem SSE is ready to use active cartridge files, that is files that contain routines in binary code.\par
If a cartridge file starts with CUB3 as first four bytes (at $0), then Steem SSE will read the two 4 byte values at $20 (32bit builds) or $40 (64bit builds) as an offset to the binary of a C function, and  as the lentgh in bytes of this function.\par
In the far future Steem SSE for Linux will read at offsets $60 and $80 instead of $20 and $40 (not implemented yet).\par
That way, one cartridge can be used by all 32 or 64 builds.\par
The function is declared as:\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\cf7\f4 /*  pointer to function\par
*   ad=address bus value, 23 significant bits A1-A23\par
*   rpin=table of booleans representing pins of the chip rpin[0]=bit 0\par
*   for Cubase 2, rpin[8] to rpin[15] represent D8-D15\par
*   for Cubase 3, rpin[8] represents D8\par
*   return value=data bus value\par
*/\par
extern "C" WORD (*CartridgeCheck)(DWORD ad,BYTE *rpin);\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\par
The routine will be called at each cartridge access (ROM3 signal).\par
Notice that "CUB2" cartridge files are not supported for the moment because a check is necessary at each Upper Data Strobe, which is some load.\par
Because Cubase 2 and 3 for Atari are not freeware, those cartridge files are not released anyway, but if you're smart you can make your own!\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 TOS (ROM)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 TOS officially stands for \i The Operating System\i0 .\par
\par
Including the BIOS, the GEM graphic environment and other layers, the full OS, except on very early models (also emulated), was printed on ROM chips. You need an image of one of those roms to use Steem.\par
\par
Generally, TOS 1.02 is the most compatible for STF and TOS 1.62 for STE mode. \par
The Mega ST can have TOS 1.02, 1.04, or 2.06, the Mega STE TOS 2.05 or 2.06.\par
Some rare programs prefer another version (check Hints file).\par
\par
1985: TOS 1.00 (ST/STM/STF) - original ROM version\par
1986: TOS 1.02 (STM/STF/STFM/Mega ST) - blitter support\par
1989: TOS 1.04 (STF/STFM/Mega ST) - coloured Atari logo, better disk I/O, many bugfixes, faster.\par
1990: TOS 1.06 (STE) - STE hardware support\par
1991: TOS 1.62 (STE) - bugfixed version of above\par
1990: TOS 2.05 (Mega STE) - new desktop, customizable icons, HD disk support\par
1991: TOS 2.06 (Mega STE) - bugfixed version of above, support for future hardware. It could also work on a  modified STF (emulated in Steem).\par
TOS 3.0X TT (not supported in Steem)\par
TOS 4.0X Falcon (not supported in Steem)\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\b Colour code\b0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 To help you, Steem SSE will display recognised files in green and known bad dumps in red. For the moment only UK TOS are recognisable by Steem SSE, if you want other languages please communicate the CRC32 of good and bad TOS.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\b US TOS versions \b0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Using a United States TOS causes games to be run in the NTSC screen mode (60Hz). This is okay emulation-wise but a lot of ST games and demos do not work in this screen mode, and often just crash or act oddly rather than telling you why. We recommend that American users of Steem use UK TOSs for games and demos, the only time a US version is required is for word processing, due to tiny differences between the US and UK keyboards. \par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  UK and US keyboard definitions are available.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\b TOS 1.00\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\b0 The first version of TOS isn't as bugged as is often said. TOS 1.00 is much decried for its hard drive management, but it's not really better on TOS 1.02 (Mega ST), and not that bad actually, the Mega ST was a capable computer. It is relatively slow. TOS 1.04 and above feature better handling of hard drives.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\b TOS 1.06 and 1.62 UK\b0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Watch out, before Steem came along most copies of these TOSs were corrupt (because no emulator could test them properly). If you have problems with this version try downloading a new copy.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\b Language\b0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Some localised version of the TOS may be necessary for some programs.\par
If you have some trouble with a program, you may give it a try. For instance, digits need shifting on a French keyboard but no an English one.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\b EmuTOS\b0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 EmuTOS is a GEMDOS compatible operating system for Atari ST series computers. It is made from Digital Research's GPLed original sources and is a free and open source replacement for common TOS images for Atari ST emulators. It hasn't exactly the same functions and compatibility as regular TOS, but most software will run on it. It is regularly improved.\par
{{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://sourceforge.net/projects/emutos/ }}{\fldrslt{http://sourceforge.net/projects/emutos/\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22\par
The last stable version of EmuTOS is shipped with Steem SSE.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 ST Video\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Some of those settings could as well be on the \i Display\i0  page, actually the \i ST Video \i0 page was created because the \i Display\i0  page was getting crowded. They could as well be named \i Display 1\i0  and \i Display 2\i0 . The \i ST Video\i0  page concerns itself with the video output of the ST, including overscan (hence borders) and the kind of monitor, including scanlines. This is a part of emulation, while the \i Display\i0  page focuses on the PC side of video rendering, such as window size.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Monitor\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The monitor type can be \i Colour\i0  (for ST low and medium resolutions) or \i Monochrome\i0  (for ST high resolution). It was an important choice on the ST, because only the appropriate monitor could display such or such resolution. Like the ST, Steem runs in one or the other mode.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Extended monitors (*)(hack)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Also available are extended monitors; these are larger screens than a standard ST could manage but are achieved by some tinkering with the ST operating system. The only programs that have any chance of working with extended monitors are GEM applications (windows/menu bars), all other programs will crash or make a mess of the screen (there is nothing that can be done about that). Most GEM apps will fail too, but some will work and allow you to fit more on the screen than anyone could ever need! NOTE: Extended monitors only work with TOS versions above 1.02, also if you use a 4-plane resolution (e.g. 800x600x4) the ST can get very confused if it tries to change to medium resolution, so try to avoid it. You have to do a cold reset of the ST before any changes to this option take effect.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Borders\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Here you can choose whether you want to see the ST borders, and which size.\par
Some games (and quite a lot of demos) use a technique called "overscan" to display graphics in the borders, that's one reason you might want to see them.\par
\b DirectDraw.\b0  The border option affects the fullscreen mode: with borders on, Steem displays fullscreen in the 800x600 screen resolution (flip screen or straight blit modes).\par
\par
Steem SSE offers no less than 5 border sizes:\par
\f5                   Resolution     Low       Medium     High\par
  Border  \par
  Off                         320x200    640x200   640x400\par
  Normal                      384x270    768x270   768x540    \par
  Normal (US TOS)             384x242    768x242   768x484    \par
  Large                       412x275    826x275      -\par
  Max                         416x283    832x283      -\par
\f1\par
The normal size for the US TOS has fewer scanlines because the ST typically operates at 60Hz. This is applied whenever Steem SSE is resized.\par
Why various sizes, while other emulators only offer one? There are many reasons.\par
- Bigger display sizes in Steem SSE use various tricks and hacks and there's always a risk something is broken, so we keep the original size available. Palette change timings were especially trouble during development.\par
- There's a performance hit for larger displays.\par
- Not all real monitors display the full border, in particular modern LCD screens or the original Atari monitors would typically display the same borders as Steem does in normal mode, therefore it is most realistic.\par
- Normal size may be merciful when the program displays trash in the border, typically because the programmer couldn't see it.\par
- Only the normal (or no) border makes sense for monochrome emulation.\par
- Most programs, including games, don't display video in the borders at all, and they shouldn't as this is beyond specs.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 ST aspect ratio\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The typical ST screen's pixels were vertically stretched, this option emulates that aspect ratio. The 60Hz mode on a 50Hz screen, very stretched, is emulated if borders are disabled.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Scanlines\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This makes Steem display black lines between actual video lines ; this may or may not be quicker than doubled lines but looks pretty ugly to some people. To others, it may be part of the emulation. Some people insist on crisp scanlines, others want filters and interpolation.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Single pixels\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The same as scanlines, but vertically.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 CRT (D3D)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Emulates a Cathode Ray Tube screen (maybe the youngest people have never seen a real one!) using SweetFX by CeeJay.dk, which should be in your plugins folder, under the name of d3d9sweetfx.dll.\par
You can change all parameters, but not inside Steem. In Steem SSE, there's just this option to toggle the effect, keys won't be transmitted to the plugin (depending on the settings).\par
If you don't like that integration, it's possible to use SweetFX the usual way, Steem D3D was already compatible with the hack.\par
This option is only available in D3D builds, and uses the power of your video card, not the CPU.\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 Creating the surfaces and switching to and from fullscreen takes more time, don't panic\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Overscan options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\cf0\b\f1\fs22 Hardware Overscan (*)\b0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Steem SSE can emulate two hardware overscan circuits, either \i Lacescan\i0  or \i Autoswitch\i0 . You need appropriate ST drivers and should use TOS 1.04. For technical reasons those devices weren't available on the STE. \par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\b Software Overscan\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\b0 There is a trade-off between emulation accuracy and performance.\par
\par
\b None\b0 : Normal video output, most video tricks (abusing the GLUE, the MMU, the Shifter*), generally called "Shifter tricks", are not emulated as there is no overscan check during emulation. This is actually enough for most programs, including most games, as overscan wasn't part of the ST specification, but many demos won't display correctly. Who watches demos anyway, right? Spectrum-512 emulation will still work (palette changes on the fly).\par
\f6\fs18 *: GLU(E): General Logic Unit; MMU: Memory Management Unit; Shifter: combines and displays video pixels\par
\f1\fs22\par
\b High-level (C2)\b0 : Efficient emulation using knowledge of often used "Shifter tricks". It should run almost all games and demos. CPU use varies with what is being emulated but is generally low. \par
\par
\b Low-level (C3)\b0 : Directly emulates the video chips, the option is available only if the \i STVL\i0  plugin was detected. It hasn't been released yet, so it's normal if the option is greyed out. CPU use is constant (per resolution) but high.\par
\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  You should choose \i None\i0  if you run regular programs, including regular games. This will make Steem SSE more efficient.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  For technical reasons, just displaying this option page causes an  internal update of video emulation! It could possibly cause glitches if emulation is running.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Wakeup options (*)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This is a very technical point, related to variable latency in some electronic chips. Normally you'll use these options only if the display of some demo isn't correct without (see the Hints file). \par
\par
You can adjust the wakeup settings for the GLU(E) and for the Shifter.\par
\par
The GLU wakeup option allows you to choose one of the 4 wake states of the STF. On the STE, the value is 1 and can't be changed.\par
\par
The Shifter wakeup option changes the precise cycle when the pixel is matched to the palette. If it isn't what the program expects, you can see some artefacts on \i Spectrum 512\i0  pictures (blame the ST and the programmers for that, not the emulator!) The default (0) should be most compatible.\par
\par
\i Random on boot\i0  randomises GLU and Shifter wakeups so that you get the delightful surprise as on real hardware.\par
\par
\i Unstable Shifter\i0  alters some aspects of high-level (C2) or low-level (C3) software overscan emulation. \par
C2: Option needed to emulate the \i beeshift\i0  effect and some other cases (\i Overdrive/Dragon\i0  for instance, or some demos that claim no emulator can run them).\par
C3: Likelier to get Shifter bands and other funny glitches if you change the wakeup!\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Display\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\expndtw0\fs24\lang2057 Frameskip\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This is a very useful option for slower processors. Drawing the screen takes quite a bit of PC CPU time so skipping frames is a very effective way to speed things up to the same speed as a real ST. Auto frameskip makes Steem skip up to 8 frames dependant on how fast it is running. \par
If possible, \i None\i0  is the best option because auto frameskip always induces some glitches.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Reset Video\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\sa200\sl240\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Steem SSE will release the DirectX video resources then reacquire them again, sometimes it works.\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Use video buffer\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Steem SSE will prepare each scanline in an intermediate buffer before copying it to the video buffer (wherever it is, controlled by the driver). The effect on speed and CPU use may vary according to the system and what Steem is emulating, usually unchecked is more efficient, checked more stable.\par
There's also a difference in the way optional scanlines are rendered.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Microseconds\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Use precise hardware counters to time video rendering, if it's not checked milliseconds are used. Microseconds allow emulating the real video frequencies, which are fractional. Timing of display still depends on the hardware and OS (better with FreeSync). \par
This setting is ignored when VSync is engaged.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 BFI (D3D)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 BFI stands for \i Black Frame Insertion\i0 . Steem SSE will update the display at twice the ST rate, one frame will be black, one frame will be the emulated image. It results in less movement blur, but video gets dimmer and some flicker may be perceptible.\par
This option operates in windowed and fullscreen modes, with or without VSync, but better with VSync. The screen must be set at a high frequency or in FreeSync.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Timing Loop\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Steem SSE will start a hard polling loop so many milliseconds before the planned time of blit (video rendering). A higher setting means more CPU use. Generally 2ms seems to be a good compromise (1ms is the previously hardcoded setting). \par
However, if your PC is very busy, no matter how high the setting, Steem SSE may lag. The general\i  \i0 option \i Make Steem high priority\i0  has a greater impact here.\par
This setting is ignored when VSync is engaged.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Stretch Filter (Direct3D)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 One of the standard D3D filters is applied when the image is stretched. It can blur the picture a little and reduce distortion. This setting applies to both windowed and fullscreen modes.\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 Even if you don't explicitly select a stretched display option, Steem SSE may need to stretch the picture to make it fit in the window\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Triple Buffering (DirectDraw)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This used to be useful to eliminate tearing or ghosting, at the price of quite higher CPU use in windowed mode on Windows XP.\par
Window compositing, a feature introduced in Windows Vista and enforced (can't disable) in Windows 8, could interfere with this. Compositing does its own triple buffering, without CPU use penalty.\par
Generally, this option isn't necessary anymore.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Windowed Mode\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Four sizes are available. With \i Show all settings\i0  option, you can choose for each resolution.\par
\i Stretch \i0 makes Steem use the video card to convert the image from the ST output size to the size of the window. No Stretch will make Steem draw the ST screen larger in order to avoid stretching. \par
If \i biggest \i0 is still too small for you, it's possible to just make the window bigger by stretching it the usual way. Check on the status bar for a precise multiplier. To keep the size through session, uncheck the following option.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Automatic resize on resolution change\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 There is also the option of whether Steem should automatically resize its window or not when the ST resolution changes (also on reset, starting Steem).\par
This can have an impact on performance if an ST program changes resolution all the time.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Lock aspect ratio\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 With this you may drag all you want, the window will keep the same proportions. Steem SSE also keeps the normal aspect ratio for all window sizes, which may introduce blur or artefacts. For instance, the \i big\i0  size in medium resolution (corresponding to x3 in low resolution) uses a non integer multiplier.\par
If the option isn't checked, you're free to change the aspect ratio of the emulated screen and some window sizes have a different aspect ratio. For instance, the medium resolution may be twice larger horizontally.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Stretch\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Choose between the two rendering modes. Stretch allows you to use a filter. Non-stretched has smaller OSD.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 VSync\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This version of vertical synchronisation is for windowed mode. \par
\b DirectDraw\b0 : Steem uses some CPU power to adjust speed.\par
\b Direct3D\b0 : Speed is adjusted at no CPU cost by the system.\par
Speed adjustment means that emulation speed isn't realistic anymore if the display refresh rate significantly differs from the ST rate. Note that even if your hardware displays at 50, 60 or 72Hz precisely, the real ST has a slightly different refresh rate based on its main clock.\par
VSync works with double frequencies (e.g. ST 50Hz/PC 100Hz).\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 The ST can operate in 3 frequencies, 50Hz (PAL, "Europe"), 60Hz (NTSC, "USA") and 72Hz ("Monochrome"). Some programs change the frequency all the time to trick the hardware, but hopefully there's still one main frequency, generally 50Hz.\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 It may depend on hardware/OS, but VSync only works on the primary monitor (main display), even if Steem is on the second monitor. Notice that it is very easy to switch the main display.\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 For a long time, LCD screens defaulted to 60Hz and had no 50Hz mode. It was a miserable period for emulation. Thanks to the HDMI requirement, a lot of screens now do 50Hz. Steem SSE can also use 100Hz as if it were 50Hz.\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 Many screens and video cards now offer G-Sync or FreeSync. With this you can get smooth animation at every ST frequency without changing your display settings. You can check that with the early Automation menu disks (0 for 60Hz). It's still not always as smooth as VSync, for various possible reasons, but the emulation speed is more realistic.\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 If you use G-Sync or FreeSync, don't check VSync\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 Process priority (general\i  \i0 options) makes a difference\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Auto VSync\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 With this option, VSync will be enabled only when the main display refreshes at a frequency close to the ST frequency (+-2Hz).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Old sync\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f3\fs22\lang12 Use this if your computer has trouble with the way recent versions of Steem SSE handle video synchronisation and you feel nostalgic for good old Steem. \par
When it's checked, settings for microseconds and the hard loop have no effect.\par
\f1\lang2057\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Screenshots\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 These options configure where screenshots are saved. \par
\par
You may also choose the format options here.\par
\par
The last option is \i Minimum size screenshots\i0 , when checked this will make Steem always save screenshots at the smallest size possible for the resolution, this is handy for people taking screenshots to put on a website.\par
\par
Warning: Sometimes this might make a mess as Steem will have to shrink the picture, but this is never a problem if you are using \i Stretch\i0  mode for drawing (see the Fullscreen options and Display/Window Size options).\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Fullscreen Mode\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\cf5\expndtw0\fs24\lang2057 Go Fullscreen Now/Go Windowed Now\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 The top button in this page allows one to toggle between windowed and fullscreen modes. You may also assign shortcuts to enter or toggle fullscreen mode (alt-enter also works).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Fullscreen on Maximize Window\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 You can change Steem's behaviour on hitting the maximize button. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Fullscreen GUI\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The fullscreen GUI is handy if it works. No guarantee. Blame Microsoft and video card drivers for all bugs. \b\par
\cf4\b0 Tip\cf0  On Windows 10, it doesn't work well in D3D builds for true fullscreen, and when it hangs, it's hard to come back to a normal desktop. The option is disabled for true fullscreen modes, but this can be overridden in the ini file for those who have an older OS (see INI file options).\par
If the option is checked, you can leave fullscreen mode by clicking on the blue icon (second from the right) of the interface, or pressing alt-Enter.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Stretch (D3D)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Choose between the two rendering modes for fullscreen. Stretch allows you to use a filter. Non-stretched has smaller OSD.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 VSync\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This version of vertical synchronisation is for fullscreen, including Windowed Borderless. See the remarks in \i Display\i0 .\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Auto VSync\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 See  \i Display\i0 .\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Triple Buffering\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 One more buffer is used in video rendering. It could fail on some systems. The exact way it works (or not) depends on your system, generally it's a FIFO queue, which means an extra buffer may increase latency.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s4\sb40\cf2\f2\fs24 Aspect ratio\i\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\b\i0\f1\fs22 Screen\b0 : resolution of your PC monitor, \b correct\b0 : magnified resolution of the ST, \b crisp\b0 : could be (much) smaller but no distortion.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Mode\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The option is different in DirectDraw and Direct3D builds.\par
In DirectDraw builds, this is a bit of a confusing option, you really don't need to know what the possible settings mean, but which is best will be different depending on your computer's hardware, try them all to see which is quickest. \i Stretch blit\i0  makes Steem draw small and then use the video card to stretch the resulting image to fill the screen, at your chosen resolution. This can be slow on very old, bad video cards, and on many video cards it causes the image to be slightly blurred ("alpha-blitted"), which makes it better resemble the bad televisions usually plugged into STs. If this blurring annoys you, switch to the first modes. In those modes, colour pixels are doubled and Steem uses the 800x600 resolution if borders are displayed, 640x480 if not. Screen Flip is not recommended for monochrome monitor emulation if the screen refresh rate is inferior to 72Hz. In the DirectDraw builds, Windowed Borderless is one of the listed modes. In Windowed Borderless mode, Steem SSE uses the native resolution and its own calculations of the drawing zone. In medium and high resolutions, the picture could be crisp but small, or big but distorted. It's because there are already many pixels in these ST resolutions.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  Try with border off\par
In Direct3D builds, the option isn't available when the Windowed Borderless Mode option is checked. This lists all D3D 32bit fullscreen modes that are available on your video card. You just select the one you like. Note that whether a mode works or not also depends on your display and your other options. Only some monitors will display 320x200 or 320x240 properly. On a LCD screen, you may go for the maximal resolution (the same as your desktop). Steem SSE will then compute how to display the biggest possible ST screen for the aspect ratio.\par
All true fullscreen modes require some time to adjust to the settings. It's a Windows feature. In D3D builds, true fullscreen on a secondary monitor is possible.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Scanlines (DirectDraw)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When you are in \i Straight Blt\i0  or \i Screen Flip\i0  drawing mode, \i Scanlines\i0  makes every other vertical line black, this can make the display a bit dark but it can also make Steem run quicker. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Use 640x400 (DirectDraw)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This option makes the screen switch to 640x400 pixels when you run in fullscreen. This means the ST display will fill the entire screen instead of having small borders to the top and bottom. You can only use 640x400 mode when borders are set to \i Off\i0 , and if the mode is available on your video card.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s4\sb40\cf2\f2\fs24 Use desktop refresh rate (D3D)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This will bypass the Hz setting in Mode, using the current desktop refresh rate instead. It can be useful if the video card can force a refresh rate that is not officially supported by the display (or its driver). \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s4\sb40\cf2\f2\fs24 Windowed Borderless Mode (D3D)\i\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1\fs22 This 'fake' fullscreen mode bypasses most other settings. You lose the benefits of true fullscreen, such as refresh rate choice, hardware lower resolution, triple buffering and possibly better performance (Steem isn't as demanding as a 3D game so no worry), but it may be more compatible with a variety of computers. It is also faster to go in and out.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Colour Control\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Some PC monitors/video cards can be very dark, this can make the ST display unrealistic, or even make some things that should be visible black. Here are some simple options to fix this problem, just fiddle with the two values until in the colour bar display you can see colours above the number 2 and the colours above 15 and 16 are a different shade. Sometimes other colours on the screen can make this difficult, to get around that click on the image of the bars to make it fill the whole screen.\par
Steem SSE also includes controls for gamma correction, one slider for all colours, or one slider per RGB colour (*).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Reset\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The power of computers, no need to reset everything yourself.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Full spectrum\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 We adapt the scales to get brighter colours on both the STE (4096 colours) and the STF (512 colours). It's not a trick, we just extend the values used on the PC side.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 B/W\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Black & white screen using the greyscale technique.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Green\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 A nostalgic emulation of the Philips CM8833 Green button.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 On Screen Display (OSD)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 The Steem OSD is there to look pretty and give information, it can be configured to suit your needs.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Logo\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 You can configure how long the 'Steem' logo will be displayed after you start emulation.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Speed bar\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The blue bar in the bottom-left corner indicates the current speed of the emulator compared to the refresh rate of the monitor on a real ST - if the bar is full it is drawing at the ST sync rate. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 State icons\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 These icons tell you whether the emulator is running, fast-forwarding, sound recording or just stopped.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 CPU speed indicator\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This icon appears next to the speed bar when you have ST CPU Speed set to more than 8 megahertz.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Time\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 If you ever wonder how much time you waste on Steem, this is the control for you. Mercifully it resets at each cold reset.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Debug info\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Some information will be displayed on the top left corner of the window or on the status bar:\par
\lang1036 EXC\tab CPU exception number\par
\lang2057 OVR\tab keyboard ACIA overrun\par
PRT\tab printing\par
CRC\tab disk checksum error\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 FPS (Frames per Second)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 With this frame rate counter, Steem can reveal the hard reality about some of those games.\par
Palette changes are ignored. It's not guaranteed to work with everything due to the technique used, based on video registers VBASE and VCOUNT, and a simple checksum of the video memory.\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24\par
Disk access light\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This is a small light that appears in the top right of the screen, it emulates the light that was on the right hand side of a real ST, except that the led is green for reading, red for writing, yellow for hard disk. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Drive track info\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Alternatively, this will display current drive, side, track and sector, like those devices some people had attached to their ST. Track is the current drive cylinder, sector is the WD1772 SR register.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Scrolling messages\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 After a while, they're not so useful anymore and can be distracting, so you can turn this off.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Bad jokes\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 For those scrollers that never were useful.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Disable on screen display\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This will disable all elements of the on-screen display.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 No OSD on stop\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang6153 Stop is then delayed by one frame. This is useful if you want to take screenshots or want the colour count.\lang2057\par
\lang6153 DirectDraw: could be necessary for correct screenshots\par
\lang2057\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Sound\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\expndtw0\fs24\lang2057 Mute sound\par
\cf0\f3\fs22 You can change it live, hopefully it won't crash.\par
\cf5\f2\fs24\par
Mute sound when inactive\par
\cf0\f3\fs22 Sound will stop when you're busy with other apps, and play again when Steem has the focus.\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\f1\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Device\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Sound Driver lets you configure which DirectSound driver Steem will use.\par
The options allow you to tweak the sound output, firstly volume. Next is frequency. If your soundcard isn't able to deliver one of the higher rates, Steem will settle for the maximum available. It makes a difference in some cases where the emulated PSG vibrates faster than 22KHz. It does happen, as the max PSG frequency is 125KHz! Most audio equipment can't reproduce above 22Hz, and your aging ears go even lower.\par
Note that 56KHz is precisely 56066 (the maximum, and rarely used rate for STE sound), 25KHz is precisely 25033 and 22KHz is 22050. The next option is format. 16bit stereo is recommended, except for some rare STE demos that insist on mono sound.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 YM2149 Sound\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The YM2149 was the original sound chip of the ST. It is also called PSG for \i Programmable Sound Generator\i0 . The fact that you can disable it is a hack, on a real ST you can't (option Hacks).\par
\par
\i Low-level\i0  activates a lower level YM2149 emulation inspired by MAME (thx Couriersud). When it's checked, Steem SSE also uses a big sample table of the chip made up by ljbk based on measurements on an actual STF (which includes filters). Thanks to this accuracy of PSG emulation is much improved. The sound is more saturated, which is correct.\par
\par
You can then set the anti-alias filter frequency, it should be somewhere around 10KHz (the ST was no CD player). Totally right turns it off, which will produce aliasing artefacts on some tunes (except if you set the sample rate very high).\par
\par
When \i low-level\i0  isn't checked, Steem's original PSG emulation runs. It is not too bad and uses less CPU. You may then choose a filter type. Those filters are primitive but do the job.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Digital sound (STE)\par
\cf0\f1\fs22 The fact that you can disable it is a hack, on a real STE you can't. It is generally called DMA sound, also by Atari, but DMA (Direct Memory Access) on the ST is a procedure that uses bus arbitration, for disk operations and for the blitter, so it's called Digital sound in Steem SSE!\par
\cf5\f2\fs24\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Unfortunately, emulation of the ultra-cheap analog MicroWire tone controller is rather primitive.\par
\par
The YM-12db setting does what the STE should but doesn't when asked to, that is attenuate the screaming YM2149 sound so that you may hear the STE samples better. It's a hack. So is \i Slow fade\i0 , which may avoid pops when the program changes the volume too fast (\i Sea of Colour, Talk Talk 2\i0 ).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Drive sound\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Yes! This SainT feature is imitated in Steem too.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Record\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 These options allow you to record Steem's output to a wav file. Clicking on the red button begins recording, clicking on it again (or stopping emulation) will end recording. You can choose the name and location of the wav file to output by clicking on choose.\par
Alternatively, Steem can save a YM file. This is usable by STSound and other utilities. The file is uncompressed.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Keyboard/Mouse\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\expndtw0\fs24\lang2057 Low level 6301 emulation (C1)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Using code by Arne Riiber and doc by Stephane Catala - Belzebub / ST Connexion, Steem SSE features low-level emulation of the HD6301 \i intelligent keyboard\i0  (IKBD) chip. The main goal was to be able to run some (very rare!) software reprogramming that chip but it does more than that now, being better than high level emu in some cases. When you change this option, you should reset the ST. In case you're curious, the titles that reprogram the chip are: \i Audio Sculpture\i0 , \i Dragonnels\i0 , \i Froggies over the Fence\i0 , \i Transbeauce 2\i0 .\par
\par
The option also commands ACIA (the MC6850 chip) improvements, mainly more precise timings. Both the IKBD and the MIDI connector use a 6850 to communicate with the CPU, though at different speeds.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Battery\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The keyboard chip can be used to keep time, and when equipped with a battery, keep time when the ST is switched off too. There's an option for being 2000-ready, which original hardware wasn't. Ticking this option off may be more compatible as most STs had no such battery.\par
 \cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf1\expndtw0\b\fs24\lang2057 Keyboard\cf5\b0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Here you can configure the keyboard. This is an area that many people have problems with because most non-English PC keyboards are vastly different from their ST counterparts. The important thing is that your PC keyboard language, TOS language and ST keyboard language all match, that gives you a chance of having the right characters appear for the right keys.\par
When the \i Shift and alternate correction\i0  option is checked this makes Steem do its best to get round the differences between ST and PC keyboard layouts by fooling the ST into thinking you are pressing keys you aren't. This works well for GEM programs but it could cause problems for games and any other program that reads the keyboard directly. \par
\par
The last choice in the language list, \i Mapping file\i0 , allows you to select an ini file that contains key definitions. Definitions are included in the package for the German and the French keyboards, which should be the most used beside English. Also included are definitions to use US or UK keyboard on UK or US TOS, it could be handy.\par
The point of the feature is to allow you to create your own file in case you're not satisfied with Steem SSE's hardcoded mapping.\par
The file format is as follows. \par
\cf8\f7\fs20\lang1033 # = comment, at start or end of line\par
entry format: 5 fields, each followed with a ; and return\par
1;22;33;44;\par
1: PC key to type (1 character)\par
2: ANSI code of PC key to type (2 characters)\par
3: Alt (a) and Shift (s) modifiers of PC key to type, if any (2 characters)\par
4: ST scancode, hexadecimal without header (2 characters)\par
5: Alt (a) and Shift (s) modifiers of ST key (2 characters)\par
The length of each entry must be the same, insert spaces where appropriate\par
The ; separator must end each field including the last one\par
Empty lines allowed\par
You may type the PC character, the ANSI code, or both. If there's a code,\par
Steem uses it. If not it uses the character. Both ANSI and UTF-8 encoded\par
characters should work, but the code, if any, must be ANSI (Windows-1252\par
actually), not UTF-8.\par
When you need to press shift or alternate (Gr) on the PC, field 1 contains\par
the 1st character of the key, not the character you want to see.\par
For instance, on a German keyboard, you need to press Alt Gr and < to\par
get |. The entry is: <;  ;a ;2b;s ;\par
In Steem, you don't use Alt Gr, you use Alt instead, like on a ST.\par
Both ANSI and ST scancode are two digit hexadecimal numbers.\par
\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057\par
Please share it if you get it working. The file may be in Windows-1252 or UTF-8 format (unicode).\par
There is also the option to manually remap the keys using shortcuts (see below).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Click (Linux, hack)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 People like some feedback when they type. Atari thought about it, but instead of  equipping the ST with expensive clicky keyboard, they provided the sound in software. Note that the Mega ST had a mechanical keyboard, excellent but not clicky (Cherry MX Black).\par
The sound may be disabled in the control panel, but this isn't always available (games that must boot the system...)\par
So in Steem SSE you can disable it directly. In some cases it should remain enabled though (see Hints), so the best is to disable it only when it's annoying you.\par
In Windows builds, this option doesn't exist anymore, you can switch the click with the control panel (but the option isn't saved).\par
\par
\cf1\b\f2\fs24 Mouse\cf0\b0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Capture\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Off: the mouse isn't captured unless you press F11 (even if you click in the window).\par
On: Steem SSE grabs the mouse when running, frees it when stopping. F11 can free the mouse.\par
Auto: Steem SSE grabs the mouse if it was captured at the last stop. F11 toggles and clicking in the window grabs the mouse.\par
Auto-release: i\f3\lang12 t's like auto but the mouse will be released each time a program is run. Useful if you need the mouse only to launch the program in GEM. \par
\f1\lang2057\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 VM-friendly\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This option helps when Steem is run in a virtual machine (works with VirtualBox, VMware). Another method is used to poll the mouse, and the cursor isn't bounded by the window frame (haven't found a way TBH). Some people actually prefer this way, even without a virtual machine.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Hide pointer on blit\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Some video cards can make a mess when the PC mouse pointer is over the Steem window, with this option on that will never happen as Steem hides the mouse before drawing to its window. This can however cause the PC mouse to flicker while Steem is running, if that is a problem try turning it off and see if your video card is one of the messy ones.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Speed\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 There's also a mouse speed dial.\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 Changing your PC mouse settings may help, the fact is that mice today are fast and not so precise. They are set up to rapidly go through thousands of pixels, the ST mouse was much slower and not accelerated.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 I/O Ports\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 This page configures the emulated ST's link to outside hardware. There are sections for parallel and serial ports , as well as a section for various adapters. The MIDI port is handled on the MIDI page. To set up a port select one of the options from the box next to \i Connect To\i0 . When you do the section will fill up with options related to the connection you chose.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 MIDI Device\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When you select this you must then select the PC MIDI device you want the ST's messages to be sent to and the PC MIDI device you want to be able to send data to the ST. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Parallel Port (LPT)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This allows you to connect an ST port to one of your PC's parallel ports. The only option is to choose which one. Warning: This may not work on all versions of Windows. See the FAQ for information on printing from Steem. Note: that port is generally not featured anymore.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 COM Port\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 By selecting this option, you can connect an ST port to one of your PC's COM ports. Again, just select the required port. Warning: This may not work on all versions of Windows.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 File\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Using this option, you can send all output from an ST port to a file. Click on the \i Change File\i0  button to open the file selector where you can select the output file (you can create a new one by typing in a new name and clicking \i Open\i0 ). The file will record the raw data (see below, SMM804).\par
The \i Reset Current File\i0  button will delete everything that is currently in the file, it will also close (not delete) currently open RTF or PBM files and reset the page counters for those. \par
You can't use a file for input.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Loopback (Output->Input)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Selecting this will cause anything that is sent to the port to be then received by the port, what use that is I really don't know!\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 TCP/IP\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 With this, you should be able to connect with someone else on the internet through Steem SSE. One instance of Steem SSE can play server (write \i server\i0  as address), the other can play client (type the address or the IP of the server). Reselect the TCP/IP option to start the connection if you change the address or the port. The server should be started first. It will probably trigger your firewall. The server can have multiple clients, if you think it's a bad idea or if your machine is client, just leave the option at 1. To terminate the connection, select the \i None\i0  option. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Various\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Some (simple) dongles are emulated. You can select one in the Ports page. For joystick port dongles, option C1 ('Low-level emulation' on the Keyboard/Mouse option page) must be checked.\par
This section also covers some other adapters:\par
-Pro Sound Designer: soundcard used by \i Wings of Death\i0  and \i Lethal Xcess\i0 .\par
-Switches for Ultimate Ripper Cartridge and Multiface ST.\par
\par
This is also the place where you can engage options for a dot matrix printer (SMM804) or a laser printer (SLM804).\par
When printing is detected, Steem automatically opens an RTF file in the selected print folder. This file may have formatted output (bold, italics, etc.) \par
When graphics printing is detected (such as printing the screen using alt-help), or the Laser printer is used, Steem automatically opens a PBM file per page in the same folder. Sorry, no PDF!\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 MIDI\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Here are some options that affect the PC side of Steem's MIDI emulation.\par
Remember that the ST side is also affected by ACIA emulation.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Use DirectMusic\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f3\fs22\lang12 The DirectMusic drivers allow greater precision and potentially eliminate MIDI jitter, provided your audio interface has the correct drivers. This uses the DirectMidi library by Carlos Jim\'e9nez de Parga.\f1\lang2057\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Use timer\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Try to time MIDI out using a Windows timer. This is not very precise and could be worse accroding to your system.\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24\par
Use Sleep\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The "Sleep" Windows function is a way to wait for an event. If it isn't checked, Steem SSE will use SwitchToThread instead. Normally SwitchToThread is better and Sleep consumes more CPU power.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Volume\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Not that useful but here nevertheless. It won't work for all devices.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Device choice\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Like the \i I/O Ports\i0  page.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Sysex (system exclusive)\par
\par
Raw MIDI\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Don't interpret data as MIDI messages (no SYSEX at all).\par
With this and the TCP/IP port, you could be able to play MIDI Maze with other idiots on the Internet. That is, if that works, which would be surprising. \par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24\par
\i Allow running status for output/input\i0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Normal MIDI messages are made up of one status byte that describes the message and then one or two data bytes. If a program wants to send the same message again it can leave off the status byte and just send the data. By default, Steem doesn't allow this and adds the status byte itself if it has been omitted, but this could cause problems to programs that require a very high transfer rate. \par
These options mean that running status will be passed on to Windows which has to decide what to do with it, so if you are having problems with MIDI tempo you can try this.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\i\f2\fs24 Sysex Buffers\i0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The number of system exclusive buffers affects MIDI when it is sending/receiving many small system exclusive messages quickly. If the number of buffers is too small, it is possible for there to be so little time between messages that Steem is still busy with all the buffers when a new sysex message arrives (and therefore part of it gets lost). If you find some MIDI program having input or output problems that sound like this it's worth a try increasing the number of buffers, something like 6 should do the job for almost anything. The size of the buffers allows you to choose the maximum length of message Steem can send or receive. This is important if you are transferring large memory banks from the device to the ST and vice-versa. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\i\f2\fs24 Input speed\i0\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This option allows you to slow down the speed Steem feeds any received data from the MIDI device to the ST. Due to restrictions of Windows Steem sends all data as fast as possible to the ST regardless of the speed it was actually sent by the device, but some ST programs can't handle that. If you have problems with receiving bank dumps it might be an idea if you slow this down a bit. Also related to this is the shortcut action \i Pause until next SysEx\i0 , this can get around time-outs on ST programs waiting for a bank dump to start. See the shortcuts section for details of how to assign this action to a key/combination of keys.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Configurations\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 This page allows you to store many different Steem configurations and use them when you like. To make a new file containing the current Steem configuration click on \i New\i0 . You can then restore it at any time by selecting it and clicking on \i Load\i0 . Be careful though as your configuration before you load another one will be lost forever. \par
Below is a list of sections that affect loading configurations, you can enable or disable each section. This allows you to only load specific options in Steem and keep other options that you don't want changed. As in macros (see below) you can organise all your configurations using the \i Configurations \i0 folder display.   \par
For example, the 520 ST configuration would have 512KB memory and TOS 1.0, maybe a single-sided drive, the 1040 STFM would have TOS 1.02.\par
You can set up some configurations for STF, STE, Mega ST, Mega STE colour or monochrome, with GEMDOS or ACSI hard drive emulation, etc., and then select one in one click rather than manually changing all the settings. The config must have the exact same name as the model. STF will work, 520 STF will not.\par
If you want to change startup options, such as starting in full screen, you should first select the config then change the option.\par
Please be advised that the whole configuration is saved, the checkboxes are for loading only some parts of it.\par
When you save a configuration, the paths to the ROM folder and to the home folder aren't saved. Paths to the current TOS and disk image files in floppy drives are made relative to those folders. That way, config files are more portable.\par
  \par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Record Input\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 This is a handy feature that will allow you to record sequences of input in to the ST and play them back later as macros. At the top there is a display of your macro folder: each macro is stored in a file with the extension stmac, and they are displayed here (if you have any). To record a macro, first click on \i New Macro\i0 , name it something snazzy and then click on the big red record button. \par
Now go to the main Steem window, start emulation and do some sort of input (move the mouse, press a key, move a joystick). When you have recorded what you want to go back to the macro display and click on the record button again to turn it off. Don't worry about doing this too quickly, Steem doesn't start recording until some input is received and it will cut off any time on the end that doesn't have any input. Now you can replay the actions you recorded by pressing the green play button (next to the record button). \par
\par
You can have as many macro files as space on your hard drive will allow. \par
This might mean they get a bit difficult to find on the list, so you can organise them into folders using the macro folder display. Just right click to create a new folder and drag appropriate macros in there. You can also right click on the bold \i Macros\i0  folder and choose to open it in Windows explorer if you prefer to use that for your organising.\par
\par
There are 2 options that affect how macros work:\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Maximum mouse speed\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This affects recording and playing macros. Some ST programs won't accept really fast mouse movements as ST mice couldn't generally move very far in a short time. This option lets you allow for this problem by configuring the maximum speed for each macro individually.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Playback event delay\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 For most macros you will want your actions to be played back as quickly as possible (for instance in the case of clicking on a shoot button in a game). \par
This option allows you to configure how long Steem will wait between input changes, as some programs won't accept lots of very quick inputs. If speed isn't an issue then you can always set this to \i As Recorded\i0 , then playing the macro will replay the recorded events at the speed you recorded them at.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Icons (*)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 You can customise Steem's look by altering its icons. On this page you will see a box containing all the icons, just left click on one to be able to select an ico file to replace it with. Right clicking on an icon restores it to its default, click on the \i All Icons to Default\i0  button to restore them all. You can also download icon schemes to change all or just some of Steem's icons with a single click on the \i Load Icon Scheme\i0  button, go to:\par
{{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://steem.atari.st/icons.htm }}{\fldrslt{http://steem.atari.st/icons.htm\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22  (link still working)\par
or\par
{{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK https://sourceforge.net/projects/steemsse/files/Other/ }}{\fldrslt{https://sourceforge.net/projects/steemsse/files/Other/\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22\par
to see what is available.\par
\par
You can create your own full set based on the stico file.\par
This option page is not available when the big GUI is active.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 File Associations (*)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Windows programs love to associate and de-associate themselves with file types. This dialog allows you to choose which files you want to associate with Steem. Just click the \i Associate\i0  button next to the desired files, it changes to \i associated\i0 .\par
Click again to de-associate.\par
\par
Note: if you used an old version of Steem and associated files, you must re-associate with the current version (or rename the program 'Steem'). If you used a version before v.3.5.3, you should manually remove the associations in the registry, HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT part. This is because in newer versions, associations are recorded for each user, in older versions, they were for the computer, and you needed administrative rights (as was natural on older Windows versions).\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 ST Control Panel\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Imitation of the GEM Control Panel\par
The full control panel is a hack giving you direct control on some ST internals.\par
Note that if the ST program changes the palette, the panel is updated. This can be demanding on processing power.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Parameters 1 (*)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Some emulation parameters that normally should be left alone.\par
Here the MC68000 and MC68901 chips.\par
All the MFP parameters show that for that chip, Steem SSE still doesn't have a 100% accurate model.\par
In Steem SSE you can fine tune the clock of the CPU and the MFP timer clock (crystal or "xtal"). The default values correspond to typical machines. Apparently there was quite some variation, especially for the MFP xtal (was there a typo in the STE schematics?) So contrary to the CPU MHz setting, those sliders are not just hacks, they allow precise emulation of real models.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Parameters 2 (*)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Some emulation parametrrs that normally should be left alone.\par
Here, video, the floppy disk drives and the MicroWire chip.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Misc.\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Misc. stands for miscellaneous, of course, but it's easier to spell. Those are the options that don't fit in another option page.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Tool bar\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The tool bar can be hidden, in case you don't like it or you need Steem to blit on the full client area of the window. It's a technical point with practical implications: third party tools like ShaderGlass work with the client area, for example.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Menu bar\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 You can control Steem SSE with the menu instead of the tool bar. The menu isn't part of the client area (important for ShaderGlass).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Status bar\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 If you don't want the magnificent status bar, this is where you can toggle it.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Show all settings\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Steem SSE can do a lot of things but only a small percentage of users will need some of the exotic features and options. The GUI is now clearer when the option isn't checked. Extra features are indicated with (*) in this manual.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Reset settings\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Restore settings to generally compatible values.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Hacks\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This option covers three kinds of things:\par

\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Convenience hacks, like accelerating STE booting (hard drive detection is slow)\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Options that go beyond the plain vanilla ST, like faster drive, faster CPU, bigger screen, etc. Without \i Hacks\i0 , those options are not available\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Emulation hacks, at least Steem SSE is straightforward about it\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Uncheck for an authentic ST experience.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  Unchecking the option won't disable all hacks at once, it just changes the interface!\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Emu detect\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Steem includes a facility to interact with ST programs that want to communicate with the emulator. If you uncheck the option, this facility is disabled. It's still possible to detect Steem using emulation inaccuracies, but this way is unreliable since further versions are supposed to be more accurate (right?)\par
\par
The ST program writes $456D753F (ASCII for \i Emu?\i0 ) in both D6 and D7, and calls xbios function VSync ($25).\par
\par
Steem returns with $53544565 (STEe) in D6, $6D456E67 (mEng) in D7 and $FFC100 in A0, which is the base of \i secret \i0 addresses used for interaction. \par
\par
