$ffc123 trigger breakpoint (Debugger, option Emu detect necessary, but no need to write Emu?)\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Clock always correct\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When this option is checked, the various ways the system can get the date and time will be hacked to report the PC time (the little clock in your taskbar). So that if you stop emulation for a while, you still get the correct time when you resume, and not the emulated time. This covers the Gemdos software clock, the Mega ST Ricoh clock and the 6301 keyboard chip. This option can interfere with some programs.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\cf5\f2\fs24 F11 F12 Emu control\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When checked (default), F11 toggles mouse capture and F12 starts and stops emulation. If you prefer other shortcuts, uncheck...\par
\cf5\f2\fs24\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1 Pause Emu control\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When the option is engaged, Pause will toggle emulation run, and Shift Pause will toggle mouse capture. Note that the emulated ST will get the Shift key, it's a problem you don't have with F11.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\cf5\f2\fs24 Save backup snapshot on reset\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Notice the operation can cause a glitch during emulation.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1\cf5\f2\fs24 Instant machine change\cf0\f1\fs22\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Normally, changes to the ST model, memory size or ROM file apply only after a cold reset. With this option, you can make the change instant. It's a dangerous option, as it will often crash the ST or even the PC.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32\lang1033 Disk manager\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057 This window controls all the disks on the ST, and the two boxes up the top hold the disks currently in the drives. This window is resizable.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Disk Images (ST, STX, MSA, DIM, STT, IPF, HFE, SCP, STW, CTR)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Disk images are floppy disks turned into files, this is how most programs are accessed on ST emulators. For details of how to create disk images from ST floppy disks have a look at the \i disk image howto.txt\i0  that comes with Steem. You will find most images on the internet however.\par
\par
The large box at the bottom of the disk manager window shows all the disk images in the current directory. The disk manager is like a little Explorer window, you can go into a folder by double clicking on it or by selecting it and pressing return. All disk image files, zip/rar/7z/bz2/gz/tar/arj archive files and any Windows shortcuts to those types of files are shown. \par
\par
Steem SSE needs some DLL files to handle archive files.\par
-unzipd32.dll for zip files (32bit)\par
-unrar.dll or unrar64.dll for rar files\par
-ArchiveAccess.dll for 7z/bz2/gz/tar/arj files\par
ArchiveAccess.dll manages zip and rar files too if the other plugins are not available to Steem SSE. ArchiveAccess can't handle newer rar archives (v5).\par
\par
At first Steem doesn't know if some archive contains a disk image or not, so all archives are displayed in the Disk manager as ZIP floppies regardless. There is an option to make Steem SSE check inside archives, but it is slow. All archives have the same default icon "ZIP". If you hover over a disk file icon, the hint will display what kind of image the archive contains.\par
\par
To insert a disk image into a drive, drag it to the box to the right of the big drive icon (or press A or B). To remove it from the drive just drag it back out to the directory view (or press Delete).\par
\par
If you right click in the directory view a menu will pop up allowing you to create a new standard size disk image (ST), a custom size disk image (ST, MSA or DIM), a STW disk image or an HFE (Rev.1.1) disk image. High density versions are available for ST and STW.\par
\par
Custom disk images can be up to 2 megabytes in size, although larger ones can be emulated correctly, most TOS versions didn't support them, you may find they will only work with TOS 2.05+ or maybe not at all. Only some real Mega STE could handle high density disks. In Steem SSE, other models can only handle such images when Hacks are enabled.\par
\par
ST disk images contain raw data bytes without any meta information (so that emulators must guess the disk configuration, if it isn't correctly written on the disk image). MSA and DIM images also contain extra information. MSA images can be created on an ST using Magic Shadow Archiver. Steem can read compressed images, but writes back uncompressed so you should have backups, beware! DIM images can be created on an ST using \i FastCopy Pro\i0 . Steem needs all sectors.\par
\par
STW and HFE disk images include clock bits as well as data, encoded into MFM words. Those STW and HFE images are more than twice larger than ST images but allow emulating the WD1772 disk controller at a lower level, and so handling the Format command. Because they're formatted inside the emulated ST, there's no sides/tracks/sectors options. You get a raw disk full of random data, lucky you! It's up to you to format the disk exactly as you would on a ST. STW is the simplest such format. If you open a disk image in a hex editor, you will find sync marks coded as $4489. HFE is optimised for the HxC floppy emulator hardware. It's quite handy if you own such device. \par
STW images may even be bigger if they are version 2, like images converted from STX or SCP, because they contain fuzzy data and timing information.\par
\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  If you plan to write on STW or HFE disk images, turbo drive is less reliable\par
\par
Beside those ST, MSA, DIM, STW and HFE disk images Steem can create itself, it is also able to handle:\par
-STT images (read-only)\par
-STX images (read-only if using pasti.dll, read-write otherwise)\par
-IPF and CTR images created with Kryoflux hardware (read-only, need CAPSImg.dll)\par
-SCP images created with Supercard Pro hardware (read-only)\par
\par
\par
\par
A right click option allows you to convert DIM, MSA and ST images to STW. Make sure both drives are empty when you do that to avoid any interference. There's also a MFM emulation option that does that on the fly, but the extra steps take some time.\par
\par
About IPF and CTR images, as they are handled by a third-party plugin, whether they work or not is also up to this plugin. Make sure you have the last version.\par
\par
Steem SSE directly handles SCP images, there's no plugin, so any bug should be fixed in Steem SSE itself. SCP images can also be converted to STW (v2) images.\par
\par
STT is a Steem-specific format that is to be considered legacy. It is a sort of "stx light", it was abandoned when the STX format appeared, but Steem and some other programs still support it.\par
\par
STX images are handled by the pasti plugin if available, directly by Steem SSE otherwise.\par
\par
If you right click in the box to the right of the big drive icon, a context menu allows you to toggle the read-only or write-protect property (important for some games), swap disks A and B, get the previous or next disk (Disk Swapper), remove the disk, or go to where the disk is stored. Notice that it is possible to eject a writable disk without saving the changes, this is handy in case you made some mistake.\par
Write-protect is internal: it will not change the file property, when it's checked it's like the sliding tab on the floppy was up. Read-only will change the file property. When you insert a disk, the option will be set if  it's Read Only or an archive.\par
\par
Right clicking on a disk image displays a menu with a myriad of options to allow you to organise and use your disk images. \i Get CRC32 and Contents\i0  is useful if the disk image is a compilation disk, selecting it will display a list of what the disk contains. For it to work, \i disk image list.txt \i0 must be in the doc folder, and it must contain the entry. This list uses CRC32 checksums to identify files. It was based on a previous TOSEC version and misses some disk images. Some have been added in the version shipped with Steem.\par
If you right click on an archive that contains multiple disk images, you can select the image thanks to the little arrows in the menu.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  Steem is good at finding images in multiple files archives, but it can't open an archive inside an archive\par
\i MSA Converter\i0  is a great program that allows you to edit the contents of a disk and convert it to a different format. \par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  It can convert a zip file containing ST files to a ST disk image in a single click\par
\i Properties\i0  allows you to change the way Steem uses the disk, it is very unlikely you will have to change the setting from the default.\par
\par
You can also run config files (INI) from the disk manager.\par
\par
If you double click in some empty space of the main window, you go to the parent folder of the current one.\par
\par
If you don't want to use the Disk manager to select disk images, two shortcuts are available to use Windows' classic file selector instead, and you also may use the classic menu by pressing the Alt key.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Drive icons\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Left-clicking on the B: drive icon toggles drive B:.\par
\par
Right-clicking on the drive icons opens a context menu with some options to:\par

\pard{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf8\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Stop the motor if it's running you crazy. It's a hack and will not work every time.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Change your fine internal or SF314 double sided drive into a miserable internal or SF354 single-sided drive (if you were unlucky back then and feel really nostalgic, or you just need to check things). For example, \i Star Ray\i0  loads sampled music from side B if it can.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Select the drive or the side of the disk as if you were using a \i freeboot\i0  switch (don't forget to reset that later!) On drive A:, it selects the second side but on drive B:, it swaps drives so that a game can boot on the external drive, which was very useful back then.\par
{\pntext\f8\'B7\tab}Select drive sound samples. You pick the folder, the files must have those names:\i\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\i0\tab\i drive_startup.wav, drive_spin.wav, drive_click.wav, drive_seek.wav\par
\cf4\i0\tab Tip \cf0 Steem SSE for Linux recognises Wavosaur's loop markers inside a wav file\i\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\i0\f2\fs28\lang1033\par
Smart Disk Swapper\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Steem SSE's disk swapper is called smart because you don't need to create a list, Steem SSE will look for disks in the current folder or archive. Accessible through shortcuts, the classic menu or the context menu. Also see options below.\par
If the disk image is found, Steem SSE will insert it and mention the name in the status bar (or on the OSD) for a while. If not, nothing happens. Searching may take a while especially going backwards because Steem SSE must check inside archives.\par
You may assign two shortcuts for \i Previous\i0  and \i Next\i0 .\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 GEMDOS\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Another handy button on the disk manager is the GEMDOS hard drive icon. A right click opens the GEMDOS hard drive manager. You can have up to 10 virtual hard drives. To set one up select the folder on your PC and then select the letter that you want it to be on the ST. Those virtual drives are called GEMDOS drives because they're based on interception of GEMDOS commands.\par
\cf4 Tip \cf0 Like in good old TOS and DOS days, limit your file and folder names to 8 characters and max 3 character extensions: OKAY.PRG; NOT_OKAY_NONO.FOLDER\par
You need to know that this type of emulation is very convenient for you, because you just use your PC hard drive, but it is based on hacks, and in some cases, it could not work as on a real Atari, or something could work in Steem but not on a real Atari.\par
Hard drives aren't as reliable as disk images for games, most things will work but not everything. If a program isn't working properly copy it to a disk image (using the ST desktop) to see if that helps. Another option in this box is to choose which hard drive to boot from if floppy drive A is empty. You can force Steem to boot from a hard drive even when drive A contains a disk by holding down the CONTROL key when you run after performing a cold reset of the ST. ALT may force loading the floppy disk (on some TOS).\par
\par
Left-clicking on the icon will toggle GEMDOS hard drive emulation on/off.\par
\par
Notice: this emulation based on interception will only work with TOS and compatible OS like EmuTOS, not MagiC for instance.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 ACSI Hard Drives\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 There's also a hard drive icon for ACSI hard drives. Left-clicking on this icon will toggle ACSI hard drives on/off, right-clicking opens a box with setup details. ACSI (Atari Computer Systems Interface) was the cheap SCSI-like interface between the ST and a hard disk or a laser printer. ACSI emulation uses img files that contain all sectors of an Atari hard drive (data only, like an ST floppy disk image). Note that unlike GEMDOS hard drives, each ACSI device may be split into several partitions (C:, D:...). The driver you use must be able to handle each of those drives (Atari's AHDI is). \par
Two ready examples are provided in the download, images of the familiar SH204 and MEGAFILE 60 hard drives, empty save fore the drivers.\par
It is also possible to enable GEMDOS virtual hard disks at the same time as ACSI virtual hard disks, you need to adapt letters, of course. ACSI drives will take the first letters. It's handy to copy files.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\sa200\sl240\slmult1 It is possible to create hdd images using Steem SSE's interface. Enter the number of megabytes you wish (1MB=1,000,000 bytes). The file is filled with zeroes. It's up to you to make it a working hdd image. ICD Pro and other ST software may help. The feature isn't much but without it you need special utilities just to create the file.\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\par
Some programs will work with a GEMDOS hard drive but not with an ACSI one, sometimes depending on the driver. \tab In turn, ACSI emulation being lower level, it should be compatible with any alternative OS, such as Magic.\par
\par
Pasti also provides ACSI emulation, for it to work it must be enabled in the disk manager and Steem's ACSI emulation must be disabled. The hard drive image is selected in pasti itself.\par
\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  Make regular backups of your image files\par
\par
The Atari SLM804 Laser printer also uses the ACSI connection. You don't need to enable ACSI hard drives to use the printer, the option is on the \i I/O Ports\i0  page. The printer controller is hardcoded as ACSI device #7.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Home Folder\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 The disk manager allows you to select a home folder. This is where all your disk images or shortcuts to disks should be stored. You can go to your home folder at any time by clicking the third button from the left in the disk manager window. If you are away from your home folder you can quickly move/copy/create shortcuts to disks in your home folder by right mouse button dragging them to the home button. The button to the right of the home folder button sets the current folder as your home folder. Right clicking on the home button and the set-home button brings up menus allowing you to go to/set 10 quick-folder links.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 To the right of the set-home button is the disk manager options button, it brings up a menu with the following choices:\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Turbo Drive (hack)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Floppy disk drives are slow, horribly tediously slow, so optionally Steem does away with the waits and emulates disk access at impossibly high speed. \par
Unfortunately, some ST software uses, ahem, colourful ways of accessing the STs floppy disk controller that only work if the disk access is horribly, tediously slow. Even some contemporary demos poorly program the controller. \par
Though the \i Drive sound\i0  and \i Drive track info\i0  options may make this ordeal more bearable, as you can see and hear what the drive is doing, you don't get the feeling the emulator is stuck. It's emulated the way it was.\par
Generally, we don't recommend leaving this option checked with unknown disk images, it is less compatible.\par
The option doesn't operate with CTR, IPF, and SCP images. Speed for images run by Pasti is set in \i Pasti configuration\i0 .\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Count DMA transfer cycles\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 On real hardware, each time disk data is transferred to or from memory, the CPU must surrender the bus. It is correct emulation to do the same, but it can be trouble according to the floppy or hard disk emulation method (especially accelerated). This option allows you to disable the feature. \par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Automatic fast forward on disk access\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Sometimes disk access can be really slow, so this option makes Steem always fast forward when the ST is doing it. There are some programs that continue while accessing the disk, if you are going to use one of them then you should turn this off.\par
This feature is compatible with accurate disk access times, with MFM, Caps (SPS) and Pasti emulation, which means you can get both accurate and fast emulation.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Read/Write Archives (Changes Lost on Eject)\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 To access disk images in archives Steem extracts them to a temporary file and uses that like a normal disk image file. Unfortunately re-archiving the temporary file can be difficult according to the archive type. Besides, modifying an archive is questionable, maybe we just shouldn't.\par
Because of this by default all disk images in archives are treated as read-only, so they can't be changed. \par
By turning on this option you can make Steem allow writes to the temporary file, but any changes will get lost when the temporary file is deleted (the disk is ejected). \par
Some ST programs require their disk to be read/write, this option will allow you to run them without having to extract them.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Protect image files\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When this option is checked, your image files won't be changed by Steem SSE.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Connect drive B:\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 By default, Steem emulates an ST with only one internal floppy drive. It can also emulate an external drive, this is usually very useful. Unfortunately, most STs only had one drive and some programs will get confused when there are two. \par
It is usually a good idea to reset after you change this option as the ST might still think there is a drive B when really there isn't.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Enable ghost disks for protected disks\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Check this option to harmlessly save high scores or game progress with CTR/IPF/STX/SCP disk images, or other images that are read-only. STG files are automatically created when the program tries to save data on the disk, leaving your image file untouched. The image may be in an archive. STG files are simple and compact collections of sectors, only those that have been changed. The feature may interfere with some programs, in that case you only need to disable the option.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Run PRG and TOS files\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This enables direct support of PRG and TOS files. To run standalone PRG or TOS files, you need to set up a Z: hard drive that points to a PRG folder, preloaded with a DESKTOP.INF file and an AUTO folder, as provided in the download. Steem SSE will copy the file in this folder (always under the same name, so don't worry about disk waste). This should work with files inside archives. The main limitation is that it only handles single files. If the PRG needs a data file, it won't work. If you want it to work, just use the regular GEMDOS hard drive feature. Also, some programs just aren't meant to work that way. In this case they should be run from a floppy or hard disk.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Automatically Insert Second Disk\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Lots of games come on two disks, if this option is on when inserting a disk into drive A Steem will look for a second disk image with a similar name and insert it into drive B. Note that even if Steem manages to insert the second disk in drive B:, the game may still require a disk swap in drive A:. Many games had only one drive in mind unfortunately. The same for demos.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Disk Swapper Patterns\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When checked, the disk swapper will look for a name where only one number or letter changes, for example [1], 2 of 4, or Disk B. It should work in many cases, and it is fast.\par
If unchecked, the swapper will just look for the next or previous disk image in the directory or the archive.  If you so fancy, you can go through the full \i Automation \i0 set with just the disk swapper. It can be slower in large directories with lots of archives, especially going backwards, because Steem must look into all archives until a match is found.\par
When there's no previous or next file in an archive, Steem warns you first, then if you insist it looks for a file out of the archive, in the folder. The order of files is logical but can sometimes be unexpected.\par
For instance:\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl252\slmult1 Chrono Quest (B).STX\par
Chrono Quest (C).STX\par
Chrono Quest (D).STX\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1 Chrono Quest.STX\par
The first disk is last in the sorted directory. There are ways to name your files so that this problem doesn't occur. Chrono Quest (A).STX comes to mind. For the game, however, disks B to D are data-disks 1 to 3!\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Eject Disks When Quit\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This makes Steem eject all the disks from the drives when you quit.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Close Disk Manager After Insert, Reset and Run\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 If you don't like the disk manager open when you run a game, give this a go.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Pasti options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Pasti, by Jorge Cwik (ijor at {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://www.atari-forum.com }}{\fldrslt{http://www.atari-forum.com\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22 ), is a way to use the STX floppy disk format in Steem. This format allows emulation of original (protected) floppy disks of yore. Try to use the last version of the plugin (check at atari-forum).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s4\sb40\cf2\i\f2\fs24 Pasti for all floppies and ACSI\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1\fs22 Pasti can handle  ST, MSA and ACSI disk images, if you want that check this option (for examplae to go around a Steem SSE bug).\par
If the option is checked, the SLM804 Laser printer isn't available.\par
If the option is unchecked, pasti will only handle STX images.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s4\sb40\cf2\i\f2\fs24 Configuration\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1\fs22 It opens a dialog box managed by pasti.dll. It is recommended to set all speed options to \i slow\i0  for precise emulation, which is what you should expect of STX images, and to disable warnings.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 MFM emulation\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf6\f1\fs22 Auto-convert\cf0\par
That option allows Steem SSE to internally use an MFM format for ST, MSA and DIM disk images. Steem automatically converts those images to STW on insertion and back on ejection. MFM emulation is more precise. It can be slower and disk image conversion on the fly takes some time too. \par
If option \i Use Pasti for all floppies and ACSI\i0  is checked, this option has no effect on images handled by pasti.\par
\cf6 Low-level\cf0\par
STW, HFE, and other images if \i Auto-convert\i0  is checked, will be handled bit by bit as if they were SCP images. \par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Double Click Action\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This allows you to configure what happens when you double click the left mouse button on a disk image (or a shortcut to a disk image). By default, doing this will insert the disk into drive A, reset the ST and then run.\par
The same effect is assigned to the Enter key.\par
\par
\cf5\f2\fs24 Hide\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\i Hidden files\par
\i0 Files hidden in Windows explorer won't show in Steem.\par
\i Extension\par
\i0 File extensions such as zip or msa won't show.\par
\i Non-Disk Archives and Broken Shortcuts\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1\fs22 This option hides shortcuts that point to a file that doesn't exist. If you show these shortcuts, then you can right click on them and select Fix Shortcut to allow Windows to search for the target file. You may want to check this if you have many broken shortcuts that are going to stay broken to speed up displaying of their folders.\par
The option also hides archives that don't contain any actual disk images. It can be really slow if there are many archives in the folder.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Icon Size and Icon Spacing\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Save space with small icons, see more clearly with larger spaces.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Sort by\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 The disk manager can sort by date, newest first, it's useful when you point to your download folder.\par
\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf2\expndtw15\f2\fs28\lang1033 Tools\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\expndtw0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Next to disk manager options is the disk image management tools button, it brings up a menu with the following options.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Search Disk Image Database\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Steem uses the great disk image database created and maintained by Keili to be able to recognise disk images. Using this option you can search for a program to find out what disk images contain it. To download the disks have a look at Steem's comprehensive links in the General Info dialog.\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  The database, as a text file, is now updated and versioned in the Steem SSE project itself\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Open Current Folder in Explorer\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Opens the folder the disk manager is looking at in Windows Explorer.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Folders Pane in Explorer\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 When checked causes the folders pane to appear when you open a folder in Explorer.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Find in Current Folder\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 Opens a Windows find dialog with the \i Look in\i0  directory set to the current folder, useful if you have a large number of disks in many folders and you want to find one quickly.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\nowidctlpar\s3\sb40\cf5\f2\fs24 Run MSA Converter\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22 This loads the MSA Converter program that can be used to edit disk images. It needs to be there, of course.\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32\lang1033 Command-line options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Here are some useful command line options for Steem. The easiest way to run Steem with them is to make a shortcut to Steem.exe, right click on it and select Properties. In the text box labelled Target add the command line options on the end (after the " if there is one).\par
This is also how a frontend will launch Steem.\par
You don't need to add - before the options.\par
\par
 NODD, GDI - don't use DirectDraw or Direct3D, only the slow Graphics Device Interface\par
\par
 NODS, NOSOUND - don't use DirectSound.\par
\par
 .st, .msa, .stt, .dim, .stx, .ctr, .ipf, .scp, .stw, .hfe, .zip, .rar, .7z, .stz file - load disk & go. \par
If two disks are passed, then the first will go in drive A and the second will be in drive B. Autoinsert second disk won't work.\par
\par
 .prg, .tos: same as disk but those are individual ST files. \par
\par
 .img, .rom: path to the TOS file\par
\par
 .sts file - load snapshot & go.\par
\par
 .stc file - insert specified cartridge.\par
\par
 NONEW - means that if one of the above files is passed to Steem and a Steem window is already open it will be opened in the current Steem and not in a new window.\par
\par
 OPENNEW - means the opposite of NONEW, the files will always be opened in a new Steem window.\par
\par
 NOLPT - this removes the option to connect an ST port to your PC's LPT ports (that option can cause a crash on some versions of Windows).\par
\par
 NOCOM - this removes the option to connect an ST port to your PC's COM ports.\par
\par
 INI=[filename] - load [filename] instead of steem.ini.\par
\par
 TRANS=[filename] - use [filename] as translation file.\par
\par
 SOF=[freq] - stands for Sound Output Frequency. Output will be forced to [freq]Hz and all other factors will be ignored (unless setting the sound card output to [freq]Hz fails, in that case Steem will ignore this option and use its usual method of determining output frequency).\par
\par
 WINDOW - force Steem to boot in windowed mode.\par
\par
 FULLSCREEN - force Steem to boot in fullscreen mode. There's also a Startup option for that.\par
\par
 DOUBLECHECKSHORTCUTS - this makes Steem's disk manager check shortcut files more thoroughly, some people have had problems when a shortcut's target file name is in a different case to the actual file. This option makes the disk manager slower to display folders with shortcuts in them.\par
\par
 SCLICK - this option makes Steem output a click when you run and stop instead of a bump.\par
\par
 NOPCJOYSTICKS - don't look for any PC joysticks, sometimes joystick drivers do some weird things!\par
\par
 OLDPORTIO - we changed how I/O to LPT and COM ports worked in v2.4, if you are using Win9x/ME then you can use this switch if it doesn't work anymore.\par
\par
 SCREENSHOT[=path] - this tells the currently open Steem to take a screenshot. If no Steem is open, then it won't do anything.\par
\par
 ALLOWREADOPEN - this command line option makes Steem open hard drive files as read only. TOS has a bug in it that allows programs that open files for read to write to them, most versions of Windows and all versions of Linux don't allow it. Steem gets around this by opening all files as read and write. \par
This works well except in circumstances when another Windows program is accessing the same file. If you want to do that then use this command line option to open the file as read-only.\par
\par
 SCREENSHOTUSEFULLNAME - this makes Steem use the full disk name as the screenshot name, rather than just the first word.\par
\par
 NONOTIFYINIT - disable the "Steem is Initialising" box.\par
\par
 STFMBORDER - if it is not overruled by the saved options or memory snapshot, this makes Steem start as an STF.\par
\par
 NOTRACE - Steem SSE won't create a Trace.txt file with debugging info (there is also a more convenient option in the startup page).\par
\par

\pard\keep\keepn\widctlpar\sb240\sl252\slmult1\cf2\f2\fs32\lang1033 INI file options\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\f1\fs22\lang2057 Those options are inside the steem.ini file to avoid bloating the emulator interface (GUI) itself.\par
\par
\b DefaultSnapshot\par
\b0 You can define a shortcut, called "Load Default Memory Snapshot", that will load the memory snapshot you specify in the [Main] part of steem.ini, for example:\par
DefaultSnapshot=[path to Steem]\\memory snapshots\\mysupergame.sts\par
\par
\b ScreenshotWithSnapshot (D3D)\b0\par
If you add this line in the [Main] part of steem.ini:\par
ScreenshotWithSnapshot=0\par
Steem won't save a screenshot with the same name as the memory snapshot. The screenshot is loaded and displayed together with the memory snapshot.\par
\par
\b WindowTitle\par
\b0 You can change the name that is displayed as window title and in the task bar by adding a line in the [Main] part of steem.ini, for example:\par
WindowTitle=Microsoft Excel\par
It is useful if you mean to run several specialised instances, each in its own folder.\par
Limitation: mustn't be longer than 100 characters.\par
\par
\b MonochromeDisableBorder\par
\b0 If you add this line in the [Main] part of steem.ini:\par
MonochromeDisableBorder=1\par
Borders will be off in monochrome mode, except if you switch them on after the cold reset. You can also use different configurations instead.\par
\par
\b NoNotify\par
\b0 If you add this line in the [Main] part of steem.ini:\par
NoNotify=1\par
It does the same as argument NONOTIFYINIT.\par
\par
\b NoIntro\par
\b0 If you add this line in the [Main] part of steem.ini:\par
NoIntro=1\par
Steem won't run its intro proposing to add a shortcut. Useful for frontends, maybe.\par
\par
\b TrueFullScreenGui\par
\b0 By default, on the D3D builds, only the Windowed Borderless fullscreen mode can show the GUI while in fullscreen.\par
If you add this line in the [Display] part of steem.ini:\par
TrueFullScreenGui=1\par
Steem will enable the GUI option for true fullscreen too, just in case it works on older systems (XP?).\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  For example it doesn't work on my Windows 10 system!\par
\par
\b PreciseModel\par
\b0 This is for config files, not steem.ini.\par
It is possible to have the exact model you want displayed in the status bar, you just need to add a line in the [Machine] part of your configuration file.\par
For example, in the 520 ST.ini config, you have\par
PreciseModel=520ST\par
You can create a 520ST with only a single-sided floppy drive running TOS 1.0, a 520STF with a double-sided drive...\par
Notice that drive A: is always included, it cannot be disconnected.\par
\par
\b MouseAd\par
\b0 This is for config files, not steem.ini.\par
In the [Patches] section of the configuration file you can set the ST address where Steem will read mouse coordinates which it can display on the status bar.\par
The address must be in integer format and point to 2 words for x,y.\par
For example in Barbarian, the address is $62C:\par
[Patches]\par
MouseAd=1580\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  The \i Patches\i0  section of the configuration must be checked\par
\cf4 Tip\cf0  The setting will be remembered through reset, until another ini is loaded. It is also saved with snapshots.\par
\par
Here's a few if you want to create ini files.\par
